Philippine Peso Rises as U.S. Recovery Builds; Bonds Steady

-- B y   K a r l   L e s t e r   M .   Y a p
-- 
2011-02-17T08:29:37Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-17/philippine-peso-bonds-advance-as-u-s-recovery-strengthens.html
The Philippine peso climbed to a
one-week high as signs an economic recovery in the U.S. is
gaining momentum spurred risk-taking, bolstering demand for
emerging-market assets.  The MSCI Asia-Pacific Index of stocks advanced after the  Federal Reserve  raised its forecast for U.S. growth. The U.S.
was the  Philippines ’  second-largest  export destination in 2010
and, based on the latest available data, the No. 1 source of
remittances from Filipinos living overseas. Bonds were unchanged.  “The market seems to believe the U.S. is on its way to
sustainable growth and that is giving optimism,” said Antonio Espedido, treasurer at China Banking Corp. in Manila. “We will
benefit from stronger exports of our goods and people.”  The peso rose 0.4 percent to 43.405 per dollar at the 4 p.m.
close in Manila, according to Tullett Prebon Plc. It earlier
touched 43.380, the strongest level since Feb. 9.  Officials judged the U.S. economic recovery to be on a
“firmer footing,” according to minutes of the Fed’s Jan. 25-26
meeting, released yesterday.  Remittances from Filipinos living abroad climbed 8.1
percent from a year earlier to $1.69 billion in December and
totaled a record $18.8 billion in 2010, according to a central
bank report this week. Philippine export growth accelerated to
25.3 percent in December from 11.5 percent the previous month, a
report showed last week.  The $161 billion economy expanded 7.3 percent in 2010, the
fastest pace in 34 years.  The yield on the 6.25 percent bond due January 2014 was
unchanged at 5.50 percent, according to Tradition Financial
Services. A basis point is 0.01 percentage point.  To contact the reporter for this story:
Karl Lester M. Yap in  Manila  at 
 kyap5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
